[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "tension_pneumo": 0.31,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "large_effusion": 0.08,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "pulmonary_edema": 0.04,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    360[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "mass_or_nodule": 0.12,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "cardiomegaly": 0.06
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    362[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    363[0m:[38;5;10m[49m }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    364[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    365[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    366[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Performance benchmarks:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    367[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    368[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Metric | Typical Value |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    369[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |--------|---------------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    370[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | End-to-end latency (S3 event to worklist update) | 3–8 seconds |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    371[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Model inference latency (SageMaker) | 1–3 seconds |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    372[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Sensitivity (pneumothorax) | 85–95% (varies by size/type) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    373[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Specificity (pneumothorax) | 85–92% |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    374[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Sensitivity (large effusion) | 88–95% |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    375[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | False positive rate (all findings) | 5–15% per study |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    376[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Cost per study | ~$0.10–$0.15 (inference + storage) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    377[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Throughput | ~200 studies/hour per endpoint |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    378[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    379[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Where it struggles:** Small apical pneumothoraces on supine patients (the hardest finding for both AI and humans). Subcutaneous emphysema mimicking pneumothorax. Skin folds creating false pleural lines. Portable AP studies with suboptimal positioning. Post-surgical patients with expected findings that shouldn't trigger alerts. Pediatric chest X-rays (most models are trained on adults).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    380[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    381[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    382[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    383[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Honest Take
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    384[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    385[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Chest X-ray triage AI is one of the most mature applications of medical imaging AI. The research is extensive, the datasets are large, the regulatory pathway is established, and multiple commercial products exist. If you're going to deploy medical imaging AI anywhere, this is a reasonable place to start.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    386[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    387[0m:[38;5;10m[49m That said, here's what will surprise you:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    388[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    389[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Alert fatigue is the killer.** A 10% false positive rate sounds acceptable in a research paper. In practice, if a radiologist gets 20 false alarms for every true critical finding, they'll start ignoring the alerts within a week. Specificity matters more than sensitivity for clinical adoption. A missed finding is bad; a system that cries wolf constantly is useless.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    390[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    391[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The PACS integration is harder than the AI.** Getting a model to detect pneumothorax is a solved problem. Getting that detection to actually reorder a worklist in your specific PACS installation, with your specific HL7 interface engine, with your specific radiologist workflow preferences, is a 3-month integration project. Every site is different.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    392[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    393[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Model validation on your data is non-negotiable.** Published performance numbers from CheXpert or MIMIC-CXR will not match your performance. Your patient population is different. Your equipment is different. Your image quality is different. Budget for a prospective validation study on at least 1,000 studies from your institution before going live.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    394[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    395[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The regulatory question is real.** If you're building this in-house (not buying a commercial product), you're building a medical device. That means FDA 510(k) clearance, a Quality Management System, design controls, risk analysis, and post-market surveillance. This is 12-18 months of regulatory work on top of the technical build. Most health systems buy rather than build for this reason.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    396[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    397[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Radiologists are not the enemy.** The most successful deployments involve radiologists from day one: choosing thresholds, reviewing false positives, providing feedback on edge cases. The worst deployments are IT-driven projects that surprise radiologists with a new system on Monday morning.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    398[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    399[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    400[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    401[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Variations and Extensions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    402[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    403[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-finding triage with severity weighting.** Instead of binary "critical vs. not," implement a continuous priority score that accounts for multiple simultaneous findings. A study with moderate pneumothorax plus moderate effusion might be more urgent than either finding alone. The composite scoring in Step 4 is a starting point; clinical input refines the weights.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    404[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    405[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Longitudinal comparison.** For patients with serial chest X-rays (ICU patients, post-surgical monitoring), compare the current study to the prior. A new finding that wasn't present yesterday is more urgent than a stable chronic finding. This requires image registration and change detection, which adds significant complexity but dramatically improves clinical relevance.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    406[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    407[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Radiologist feedback loop.** When the radiologist reads the study, capture whether they agreed with the AI's triage decision. Feed disagreements back into a retraining pipeline. Over time, the model calibrates to your institution's specific patterns and preferences. This is the path from "useful tool" to "indispensable tool."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    408[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    409[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    410[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    411[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Related Recipes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    412[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    413[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 9.1 (Image Quality Assessment):** Run quality checks before inference; poor-quality images should be flagged for retake rather than triaged with low confidence
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    414[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 9.4 (Dermatology Lesion Triage):** Similar triage-not-diagnosis pattern applied to a different imaging modality; shares the regulatory and workflow integration challenges
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    415[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 9.6 (Diabetic Retinopathy Screening):** A step beyond triage into screening/diagnosis territory; illustrates the increased regulatory burden
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    416[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 9.7 (Radiology AI Triage, Multi-Modality):** Extends this single-modality pattern to CT, MRI, and other modalities with modality-specific models
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    417[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
